Two days and 17 hours later, we have delivered all of our senior signs. Every minute was worth it to see the smiles and excitement from our seniors and their families. Every community welcomed us and they were so happy for their neighbors! It was awesome!

Special thanks to those who made this possible!
Our sign deliverers- Mrs. Marine, Mr. Brake, Mrs. Stiles, Mrs. Lynch, Mr. Bell, Mr. Daws, and Ms. Gerni. Bus Drivers: John Davis and Leroy Tingle, Ms. M. Workman, Cpl. White, Regina Warnick, P and S Designs, JD Signs and Mr. Layton, Dr. and Mrs. Hayes, and the staff at WHS and WSD who helped and followed for hours behind our bus to cheer on our students!

Seaford School District
May 30 at 7:11 PM ·

Former Seaford Superintendent Passes Away - Dr. Kenneth C. Madden Sr. passed away on Friday, May 29, 2020 at the age of 102. Dr. Madden served as the Superintendent of the Seaford Special School District from 1952-1967. He left Seaford to become the Delaware State Superintendent of Public Instruction (This position is now the Delaware Secretary of Education.) The auditorium at Seaford High School is named after Dr. Madden. The Seaford School District has Dr. Madden's family in its thoughts and prayers. http://edl.io/n1238665

This shout out is for these teachers at Woodbridge School District's Woodbridge Middle:

To Fallon Licinski: "Science was never my strong suit...until Mrs. Licinski! She has such a big impact on her students! She is kind, thoughtful, caring, and so much more! She supports her students in anyway possible. Me best friend and I always went to each others sporting events alone until Mrs. L said she would like to as well! To John Tomeski: "Mr. Tomeski is an amazing educator! He really cares for his students and has their best interest at heart from the classroom to after school programs. We will certainly miss him next year since we are moving on to high school."

post_text: It is with great sadness that we inform you of the passing of our beloved PWES Principal, Dr. Laura Leach. Dr. Leach was a loved, irreplaceable friend and leader of her school and Woodbridge community. Her positive attitude and desire to be of service to others has touched us all. Death can be difficult for us to understand, especially when it is sudden. This difficult time can be stressful and confusing for students. In order to support our students during this difficult time, we have arranged to have counselors available remotely to assist staff and students with the questions and grief that accompany such a difficult situation. At this time, we ask to please respect the privacy of the Leach family as they mourn this devastating loss. Please keep the Leach family in your thoughts and prayers.
text: It is with great sadness that we inform you of the passing of our beloved PWES Principal, Dr. Laura Leach. Dr. Leach was a loved, irreplaceable friend and leader of her school and Woodbridge community. Her positive attitude and desire to be of service to others has touched us all. Death can be difficult for us to understand, especially when it is sudden. This difficult time can be stressful and confusing for students. In order to support our students during this difficult time, we have arranged to have counselors available remotely to assist staff and students with the questions and grief that accompany such a difficult situation. At this time, we ask to please respect the privacy of the Leach family as they mourn this devastating loss. Please keep the Leach family in your thoughts and prayers.

Today the Governor announced that students would not be returning to school on May 18 as originally hoped. Due to the continuing COVID health crisis, school buildings will remain closed through the end of this school year. Our grab and go food program schedule will continue to operate on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday each week. We will continue to work on finalizing our plans to finish out the school year and will communicate these plans in a timely manner. Thank you and stay safe.

Delaware Department of Health and Social Services (DHSS)
April 8 at 9:06 PM ·

Consistent with guidance from the CDC, the Delaware Division of Public Health recommended that Delawareans should wear cloth face coverings in public settings where social distancing measures are difficult to maintain. Those settings include grocery stores and pharmacies.

Delaware’s response to COVID-19 has been driven by science, and will continue to be driven by science. Our goal is simple. We are working to prevent a surge in cases, protect hospital capacity, and save lives. The science tells us that wearing a face covering in certain public settings can help prevent transmission and spread of the COVID-19 virus.

But wearing a face covering is not an excuse to spend more time in public. Stay home. Don’t go out in public unnecessarily. Wash your hands. Disinfect surfaces frequently. It’s important we all do our part to get through this.

LEARN MORE: https://news.delaware.gov/…/delaware-division-of-public-he…/

April 1 at 2:59 PM ·

Through an organized effort, Nanticoke Memorial Hospital and DonateDE.org are requesting donations of these items from businesses or community members who have supplies that they do not currently need. Members of the community are not being asked to purchase new items for donation.
The following unused items are needed: All types of unused protective face masks, especially N95 masks, protective suits and medical scrubs, goggles, safety glasses and face shields, cleaning and sterilizing solutions and wipes, medical gloves, hand sanitizer, disposable stethoscopes and digital and disposable thermometers. Donations can be made Thursday April 2nd through Saturday April 4th at Delaware Teen Challenge Thrift Store located at 22941 Sussex Highway in Seaford. The donation site will be open between 10:00 AM and 2:00 PM. For other donations of items to Nanticoke outside of this event, please contact Nanticoke at 302-536-5386.

You may catch COVID-19 and be at risk of becoming severely ill, if you've a noncommunicable disease/a pre-existing condition such as:
❗️Cardiovascular disease
❗️Chronic respiratory disease
❗️Diabetes
❗️Cancer

Here are tips for people affected by these conditions to stay safe:
✔️Take your medicine & follow medical advice
✔️Secure 1 month+ supply of medication
✔️Keep distance from sick people
✔️Wash 👐 often
✔️🚭 or quit drinking 🍾

shared_text:
Governor John Carney
March 26 at 6:41 PM ·

Today, we launched Delaware Housing Assistance Program to help to renters affected by shutdowns, closures, layoffs, reduced work hours, or unpaid leave due to COVID-19. The Delaware State Housing Authority (DSHA) program will provide eligible households up to $1,500 in assistance, with payments made directly to the property owner or utility company.

From restaurant workers and small business owners, to hair stylists and barbers, we know many Delawareans are facing a very challenging time as they struggle with the economic effects of the public health emergency.

We hope this assistance program will give Delaware families, especially our most vulnerable neighbors, some peace of mind as this situation continues to evolve.

Learn more and apply here: http://www.destatehousing.com/OtherPrograms/ot_dehap.php

Governor John Carney
March 24 at 4:46 PM ·

Today, I updated our State of Emergency declaration. Delawareans have a basic, fundamental right to vote. Today’s order will preserve that right and allow Delawareans to vote by absentee ballot in the presidential primary on June 2.

The additional protections in this order are essential to help support Delawareans – especially our most vulnerable neighbors – as this situation evolves. This is an extremely challenging economic situation for many of our neighbors, and we need to do what we can to support them.

Read more: https://news.delaware.gov/2020/03/24/governor-carney-moves-presidential-primary-date-to-june-2/

**ATTENTION** **Update to Grab & Go Meal Schedule **

Good morning Woodbridge Families,
We wanted to provide an update on our Grab and Go meal schedule. For the remainder of this week, we will be delivering food today, Thursday, and Friday. Beginning next week, we will be serving grab and go meals on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. We plan to continue this schedule moving forward. The meals given on each day will include two meals for the next day. Although we are limiting the number of days serving, you will still be provided meals for all seven days. All times and locations will remain the same.
Meals will be provided to all children 18 and under at no charge on a first come first serve basis. Please remember that the child must be present to receive service. Call 211 for the most up to date locations and times. We will continue to communicate updates as needed. Thank you and stay safe.

Sincerely,

The Woodbridge School District 💙

Woodbridge Marine Corps JROTC Booster Club
February 12 at 8:09 PM ·

**** Watch Targets Live with the link below: Dalton is on lane 3 just put 3 in start and finish location and you will see his scores.****

1st Lt. Dalton Cannon has qualified and is invited to compete in the Marine Individual Precision Qualifiers in Anniston, Alabama. He is one of 10 MCJROTC students in the United States; and the only one in Delaware to get this invitation as an individual shooter. If you wish to follow his competition, here are the details: He is on a 3 Relay Schedule, he is in relay 1, unless something changes these are his competition times: 2/15 - 0800-0930 and 2/16 - 1015-1200
Range: Anniston Firing Pt: 3
You can watch the competition live at this link: http://thecmp.org/competitions/live-targets/

We wish Dalton and his family safe travels and straight shooting. We want to thank the many generous supporters that donated to make this opportunity possible.

Woodbridge High School, Greenwood, DE
February 11 at 9:52 AM ·

Congratulations to teacher Dana Shelton and students Taylor Scott, Nina Burns-Skrobot, and Logan Leverage-Frye who received 2nd place in the 2020 Personal Finance Case Study Competition.
This program is designed to provide Academy of Finance students with a “hands-on” experience to apply what they have learned in their classroom. Participating teams researched the financial concerns of a hypothetical family and developed a written Financial Plan. The teams with the highest-scoring Financial Plans were invited to compete in the State Finals held at the Trading Center at the University of Delaware.
